article.description: Tiny Wagner College clinched a bid to the NCAA tournament for the first time by winning the Northeast Conference tournament championship Wednesday night, 78-61 over St. Francis.
article.headline: First trip for tiny Wagner, but not for infamous coach
article.linkText: Mayor Bloomberg watches Wagner dance in Northeast
article.story:
NEW YORK (AP) -- Back up the boat.

	   Tiny Wagner College can hop on the Staten Island ferry and head
for mainland New York City after clinching a bid to the NCAA
tournament for the first time by winning the Northeast Conference
tournament championship Wednesday night, 78-61 over equally tiny
St. Francis College.

	   Playing in an old-fashioned campus gym that holds just over
2,000 fans, the Seahawks (21-10) used the first-half scoring of
Jermaine Hall, NEC Player of the Year, to grab control of this game
and then just wore down the Terriers.

	   With Mayor Michael Bloomberg on hand, Wagner played a heads-up
aggressive game and never was in danger. The win was the 900th in
school history but for the Seahawks, hidden away in a corner of the
city that is usually ignored, it was the biggest one.

	   Fans rushed the court and hugged the players in a celebration
that seemed to reverberate all over the small campus.

	   Perhaps the happiest of all was Hall, who scored 27 points, 22
of them in the first half. It was the final home game for the
senior and he dominated, hitting 12 of 16 field goals and grabbing
12 rebounds.

	   The victory sent coach Dereck Whittenburg back to the
tournament, 20 years after he launched the most famous airball in
NCAA history. It was Whittenburg's shot that was grabbed by Lorenzo
Charles for the winning basket as North Carolina State beat Houston
for the championship in 1983.

	   Whittenburg seemed cool for most of the game but when Wagner
began to close in on victory, he whipped off his coat jacket and
began leading the fans in a cheer for defense.
